# Project: Constraint-Aware Site Planning Workbench

Browser-first web app. Parcel geometry + governing rules + public records → editable site scheme + first-pass underwrite. Pilot: Colorado Springs city + unincorporated El Paso County.

## Stack (decided — do not suggest alternatives)
- React + Vite + TypeScript (NOT Next.js)
- MapLibre GL JS for 2D map (NOT Mapbox, NOT Cesium)
- Three.js + React Three Fiber for 3D scheme view (Phase 1+, not Phase 0)
- Supabase-managed Postgres with PostGIS and pgvector (NOT a separate vector DB)
- Graphile Worker for background jobs (NOT Temporal, NOT Inngest) — Phase 1+
- Docling primary, PyMuPDF fallback for PDF parsing — Phase 2+
- Tailwind CSS with locked-down custom config (tokens only)
- Cloudflare R2 for object storage — Phase 1+

## Governing principles (non-negotiable)
1. Cited, versioned truth. Every user-visible rule traces to a source_snapshot.
2. Geometry lives in PostGIS, not React state. One canonical spatial store.
3. Jurisdiction (city vs county) is first-class. Two packs from day one.
4. Open/cheap default, premium gated. No Google 3D Tiles as default canvas.
5. Feasibility-grade, not survey-grade. UI never implies stamped entitlement.
6. One copilot, deterministic tools, explicit approvals. No agent swarms.
7. LLMs propose; PostGIS + typed code compute. LLMs are never the source of zoning truth.

## Current phase
Phase 0 — setup and validation. Scope: real parcel lookup + cited rules panel. No auth, no editing, no LLM, no Tauri, no R3F yet. Those come in Phase 1+.

## Design language
Tufte + Knaflic. Restrained palette: greys + two blues (accent and secondary). One thing emphasized per view. Thin rules, generous whitespace, serif for headings, sans for body. The citation panel is the product's signature visual moment — treat it with care.

## What to REFUSE when asked
- Next.js (use Vite)
- Mapbox GL JS (use MapLibre)
- A separate vector database like Pinecone/Weaviate/Qdrant (use pgvector in the same Postgres)
- An autonomous agent framework or multi-agent chain (one copilot with deterministic tools)
- Hardcoding zoning rules in JS constants (they belong in the claims table with source_snapshot links)
- Storing parcel geometry only in React state or JSON files (PostGIS is the store)
- Any framing that implies survey-grade or permit-ready output
- Reproducing copyrighted zoning text verbatim in code or seeds (use cited summaries, not full-text copies)

## When unsure
Prefer boring and portable over clever. Ask before introducing a new dependency. Prefer vanilla Postgres patterns (SQL, relations, PostGIS functions) over ORM-specific features that don't port.
